===Canada===
{{main article|Euthanasia in Canada}}
The common law crimes of attempting suicide and of assisting suicide were codified in Canada when Parliament enacted the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]] in 1892.<ref>''Criminal Code,1892'', SC 1892, c 29, ss 237, 238.</ref> Eighty years later, in 1972, Parliament repealed the offence of attempting suicide from the Criminal Code based on the argument that a legal deterrent was unnecessary.<ref name=Carter2012/> The prohibition on assisting suicide remained, as s 241 of the Criminal Code:

:Counselling or aiding suicide
:241. Every one who

::(a) counsels a person to [die by] suicide, or

::''(b) aids or abets a person to [die by] suicide'',

:whether suicide ensues or not, is guilty of an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term not exceeding fourteen years.<ref>''Criminal Code'', RSC 1985, c C-46, s 241, as amended by RSC 1985, c 27 (1st Supp), s 7.</ref>

However, the law against assisted suicide, including physician-assisted suicide, was the subject of much debate including two reports of the [[Law Commission of Canada|Law Reform Commission of Canada]] in 1982 and 1983, though these did not support changing the law.<ref>[http://www.lareau-law.ca/LRCReport20.pdf Euthanasia, Aiding Suicide and Cessation of Treatment, Report # 20, 1983. Law Reform Commission of Canada]</ref>

In 1993, the offence of assisted suicide survived a constitutional challenge in the [[Supreme Court of Canada]], in the case of ''[[Rodriguez v. British Columbia (Attorney General)]]''.  The plaintiff, [[Sue Rodriguez]], had been diagnosed with [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (ALS) in early 1991.  She wished to be able to die by suicide at a time of her own choosing, but would require assistance to do so, because her physical condition prevented her from doing so without assistance. By a 5-4 majority, the Court held that the prohibition on assisted suicide did not infringe [[Section 7 of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|s 7 of the ''Canadian Charter of RIghts and Freedoms'']], which provides constitutional protection for liberty and security of the person.  The majority held that while the law did affect those rights, it did so in a manner consistent with the principles of fundamental justice.  The majority also held that the prohibition on assisted suicide did not infringe the Charter's prohibition against [[Section Twelve of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|cruel and unusual treatment or punishment]].  Assuming the prohibition did discriminate on basis of disability, the majority held that the infringement was a [[Section One of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms|justifiable restriction]].<ref name="thecanadianencyclopedia">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/suicide|title=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=thecanadianencyclopedia.com|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=OLAD/><ref>[http://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/1054/index.do ''Rodriguez v. British Columbia (Attorney General)'', [1993<nowiki>]</nowiki> 3 SCR 519.]</ref>

In 1995 the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] issued a report on assisted suicide entitled ''Of Life and Death''.<ref name=OLAD>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/content/sen/committee/351/euth/rep/lad-tc-e.htm|title=Of Life and Death - Table of Contents|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> In 2011 the [[Royal Society of Canada]] published its report on end-of-life decision-making.<ref>[https://rsc-src.ca/en/expert-panels/rsc-reports/end-life-decision-making Royal Society of Canada:End-of-Life Decision Making. 2011]</ref> In the report it recommended that the Criminal Code be modified so as to permit assistance in dying under some circumstances.<ref name=CarterSCC>{{cite web|url=https://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14637/index.do|title=Carter v. Canada (Attorney General) - SCC Cases (Lexum)|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>  In 2012 a Select Committee on Dying with Dignity of the [[Quebec National Assembly]] produced a report recommending amendments to legislation to recognize medical aid in dying as being an appropriate component of end-of-life care.<ref name=CBCJune214>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-passes-landmark-end-of-life-care-bill-1.2665834|title=Quebec passes landmark end-of-life-care bill|date=5 June 2014|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> That report resulted in ''An Act respecting end-of-life care'', which is set to come into force on December 10, 2015.<ref name=CarterSCC/><ref name=CBCJune214/><ref>[http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=5&file=2014C2A.PDF ''An Act respecting end-of-life care'', SQ 2014, c 2, s 78];  [http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=2&file=/S_32_0001/S32_0001_A.html CQLR, c. S-32.0001].</ref>

On June 15, 2012, in ''[[Carter v Canada (AG)]]'', the [[British Columbia Supreme Court]] ruled that the criminal offence prohibiting physician assistance of suicide was unconstitutional on the grounds that denying people access to assisted suicide in hard cases was contrary to the [[Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] guarantee of equality under Section 15.<ref name=Carter2012>{{cite web|url=http://www.canlii.org/en/bc/bcsc/doc/2012/2012bcsc886/2012bcsc886.html|title=CanLII - 2012 BCSC 886 (CanLII)|publisher=|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="cbc">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/story/2012/06/15/bc-assisted-suicide-ruling.html|title=Assisted-suicide ban struck down by B.C. court - British Columbia - CBC News|publisher=cbc.ca|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>
This decision was subsequently overturned by the majority of the [[British Columbia Court of Appeal]] (2:1) on the basis that the issue had already been decided by the Supreme Court of Canada in the Rodriguez case, invoking ''[[stare decisis]]''.

A landmark [[Supreme Court of Canada]] decision on February 6, 2015<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/supreme-court-says-yes-to-doctor-assisted-suicide-in-specific-cases-1.2947487 |title=Supreme Court says yes to doctor-assisted suicide in specific cases |last=Payton |first=Laura |date=February 6, 2015 |website=CBC News |publisher=CBC/Radio Canada |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref> overturned the 1993 Rodriguez decision that had ruled against this method of dying. The unanimous decision 
in the further appeal of [[Carter v Canada (AG)]], stated that a total prohibition of physician-assisted death is unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://scc-csc.lexum.com/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/14637/index.do |title=Supreme Court Judgments  |author=no by-line.--> |date=February 6, 2015 |website=Supreme Court of Canada |publisher=SCC/CSC |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref>  The court’s ruling limits exculpation of physicians engaging physician-assisted death to hard cases of “a competent adult person who clearly consents to the termination of life and has a grievous and irremediable medical condition, including an illness, disease or disability, that causes enduring suffering that is intolerable to the individual in the circumstances of his or her condition.” The ruling was suspended for 12 months to allow the Canadian parliament to draft a new, constitutional law to replace the existing one.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/supreme-court-rules-on-doctor-assisted-suicide/article22828437/ Supreme Court rules Canadians have right to doctor-assisted suicide] Sean Fine, Globe and Mail 6 Feb. 2015</ref>

Specifically the Supreme Court held that the current legislation was overbroad in that it prohibits "physician‑assisted death for a competent adult person who (1) clearly consents to the termination of life and (2) has a grievous and irremediable medical condition (including an illness, disease or disability) that causes enduring suffering that is intolerable to the individual in the circumstances of his or her condition." The court decision includes a requirement that there must be stringent limits that are “scrupulously monitored.” This will require the death certificate to be completed  by an independent medical examiner, not the treating physician, to ensure the accuracy of reporting the cause of death.<ref>{{cite news |authors=Guichon, Alakija, Doig, Mitchell and Thibeault |date=December 28, 2015 |title=Assisted dying: Four problems, one simple solution |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/assisted-dying-four-problems-one-simple-solution/article27924838/ |newspaper=Glove and Mail |location=Toronto, Canada |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref>

The newly (November 2015) elected federal government subsequently requested a six-month extension for implementation; the arguments for this request were scheduled to be heard by the Supreme Court in January 2016.<ref name="The Canadian Press">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/health/canadian-doctors-express-mixed-opinions-on-assisted-dying-1.2715008 |title=Canadian doctors express mixed opinions on assisted dying |author=The Canadian Press |date=December 27, 2015 |website=CTV News |publisher=Bell Media |access-date=January 2, 2016}}</ref>

The Canadian Medical Association (CMA) reported that not all doctors would be willing to help a patient die. The belief in late 2015 was that no physician would be forced to do so. The CMA was already offering educational sessions to members as to the process that would be used after the legislation had been implemented.<ref name="The Canadian Press"/>

===India===
The [[Section 309 of the Indian Penal Code|Indian penal code 309]] deals with punishment for attempted suicide. The [[Mental Health Care Act, 2017|Mental Health Care Act 2017]] greatly limits the scope for the code to be implemented.<ref>{{cite news|first=Rhythma|last= Kaul|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mental-healthcare-bill-that-decriminalises-suicide-attempt-passed-by-parliament/story-iL3DXiatxP7BFhS2t4zGCM.html|title=Mental Healthcare Bill decriminalising suicide attempt passed by Parliament|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=27 March 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> The bill states, “Any person who attempts to [die by] suicide shall be presumed, unless proved otherwise, to have severe stress and shall not be tried and punished under the said Code”.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prsindia.org/uploads/media/Mental%20Health/Mental%20Healthcare%20Act,%202017.pdf |title=The Mental Health Care Act, 2017 |publisher=Government of India |accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> State governments are required to provide adequate care and rehabilitation for such individuals as to prevent a recurrence of an attempt to suicide.

===Iran===
The act of suicide has not been criminalized in the [[Judicial system of Iran|penal law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]].<ref name="firoozmand56">{{cite web | title=Freewill termination: A look into psychological and legislative aspects of suicide in Iran | website=magiran.com | url=http://www.magiran.com/view.asp?Type=pdf&ID=1017038 | language=fa | access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> However, no one is allowed to ask another to kill him/her.<ref name="firoozmand56"/> In addition, threatening to kill oneself is not an offense by the law, however if this act of threatening is done by a prisoner in a [[prison]], then that would be considered as violation of the prisons' regulations and the offender may be punished according to penal law.<ref name="firoozmand56"/>

According to the Act. 836 of the [[Judicial system of Iran|civil law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] if a [[suicidal person]] prepares for suicide and writes a [[Will and testament|testament]], if he/she dies, then by law the will is considered void and if he/she doesn't die, then the will is officially accepted and can be carried out.<ref name="tabnak">{{cite web | url=http://www.tabnak.ir/fa/news/530947/نگاهی-به-خودکشی-از-زاویه-قانونی | title=Suicide from the point of view of law | publisher=[[Mohsen Rezaee|Tabnak News Agency]] | date=September 12, 2015 | access-date=June 5, 2016}}</ref>

According to the theory of "borrowed crime", because suicide itself is not a crime in penal law, thus any type of assisting in an individual's suicide is not considered a crime and the assistant is not punished.<ref name="ettelaat">{{cite web | url=http://www.ettelaat.com/etiran/?p=35136 | title=Suicide in law and fiqh | publisher=[[Ettela'at]] | date= December 29, 2013 | access-date=June 5, 2016 | author=Amir Sharifi Khezarati}}</ref> [[Assisted suicide|Assisting in suicide]] is considered a crime only when it becomes the "'''cause'''" of the suicidal person's death; for example when someone takes advantage of someone else's unawareness or simplicity and convince him/her to kill him/herself. In such cases assisting in suicide is treated as [[murder]] and the offender is punished accordingly.<ref name="firoozmand56"/><ref name="ettelaat"/> In addition, assisting in suicide is considered a crime under section 2 of the Act. 15 of [[Judicial system of Iran|the cyber crimes law of the Islamic Republic of Iran]] which was legislated on June 15, 2009. According to the mentioned act, any type of encouragement, stimulation, invitation, simplification of access to lethal substances and/or methods and teaching of suicide with the help of [[computer]] or any other media network is considered assisting in suicide and thus, is punished by imprisonment from 91 days up to 1 year or fines from 5 to 20 million [[Iranian Rials]] or both.<ref name="firoozmand56"/>

===Ireland===
Attempted suicide is not a criminal offence in Ireland and, under Irish law, self-harm is not generally seen as a form of attempted suicide. It was decriminalised in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/1993/en/act/pub/0011/index.html |title=Criminal Law (Suicide) Act, 1993 |publisher=Irishstatutebook.ie |date=1993-06-09 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> Assisted suicide and [[euthanasia]] are, illegal. This is currently being challenged at the High Court, as of December 2012. As of 2014 assisted suicide remains illegal in Ireland.

===Malaysia===
Under section 309 of the [[Penal Code (Malaysia)|Penal Code of Malaysia]], whoever attempts to die by suicide, and does any act
towards the commission of such offence, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to one year or with fine
or with both.<ref>{{cite web|title=Act 574 Penal Code|url=http://www.agc.gov.my/Akta/Vol.%2012/Act%20574.pdf|website=Attorney General's Chambers Website|accessdate=3 July 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226041337/http://www.agc.gov.my/Akta/Vol.%2012/Act%20574.pdf|archivedate=26 February 2015|df=}}</ref>

===Netherlands===
In the [[Netherlands]], being present and giving moral support during someone's suicide is not a crime; neither is supplying general information on suicide techniques. However, it is a crime to participate in the preparation for or execution of a suicide, including supplying lethal means or instruction in their use. ([[Physician-assisted suicide]] may be an exception. See [[Euthanasia in the Netherlands]].)

===New Zealand===
As with many other western societies, [[New Zealand]] currently has no laws against suicide in itself, as a personal and unassisted act. However, as with comparable societies, there are still legislative sanctions against 'assisting or abetting' the suicides of others, under Section 179 of the Crimes Act 1961. (For further details, see [[Euthanasia in New Zealand]].)

===Norway===
Suicide or attempted suicide is not illegal in Norway. However, [[complicity]] is.<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/nb/dep/jd/dok/regpubl/otprp/2008-2009/otprp-nr-22-2008-2009-/6/5/1.html?id=540447 Justis- og politidepartementet: Ot.prp. nr. 22 (2008-2009) Om lov om endringer i straffeloven 20. mai 2005 nr. 28]. Chapter 6.5.1, page 183.</ref>

===Romania===
Suicide itself is not illegal in Romania, however encouraging or facilitating the suicide of another person is a criminal offense and is punishable by up to 7, 10 or 20 years in prison, depending on circumstances.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II/Q= | title=Penal Code of Romania, art. 191 | accessdate=5 February 2015 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308121055/http://www.just.ro/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=Wpo7d56II%2FQ%3D | archivedate=8 March 2015 | df= }}</ref>

===Russian Federation===
In Russia, a person whose [[mental disorder]] “poses a direct (imminent?) danger to themselves”{{Verify source|date=November 2012}} can be [[Involuntary commitment|put into a psychiatric hospital]].

Inciting someone to suicide by threats, cruel treatment, or systematic humiliation is punishable by up to 5&nbsp;years in prison. (Article 110 of the [[Criminal Code of the Russian Federation]])

[[Federal law of Russian Federation no. 139-FZ of 2012-07-28]] prescribes censorship of information about methods of suicide on the Internet. According to a website created by the [[Pirate Party of Russia]], some pages with suicide jokes have been [[Russian Internet blacklist|blacklisted]], which may have led to blocking of an IP address of [[Wikia]].<ref name="rublacklist">{{cite web|url=http://rublacklist.net/|title=RUBLACKLIST.NET &#124; РОСКОМСВОБОДА|publisher=rublacklist.net|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news
|url = http://hitech.newsru.com/article/02nov2012/rupirtsvscnsr
|script-title=ru:Пиратская партия России обещает открыть доступ к "неправомерно заблокированным" сайтам из "черного списка"
|language = ru
|publisher = [[NEWSru.com]]
|date = 2012-11-02
|accessdate = 2013-01-16
}}</ref> See also: [[Dumb Ways to Die#Censorship in Russia]].

===Singapore===
In [[Penal Code (Singapore)|Singapore]], a person who attempts to die by suicide can be imprisoned for up to one year.<ref>Singapore Penal Code (Cap 224, Rev Ed 2008), s 309</ref>

However, this law is rarely enforced.

===South Africa===
South African courts, including the [[Appellate Division (South Africa)|Appellate Division]], have ruled that suicide and attempted suicide are not crimes under the [[Roman-Dutch law]], or that if they ever were crimes, they have been abrogated by disuse. Attempted suicide was from 1886 to 1968 a crime in the [[Transkei]] under the Transkeian Territories Penal Code.<ref>{{cite book |last=Milton |first=John |title=South African Criminal Law and Procedure: Common-law crimes |year=1996 |publisher=Juta |location=Cape Town |edition=3rd |isbn=978-0-7021-3773-0 |pages=353–354}}</ref>

===United Kingdom===

====England and Wales====
{{See also|Felo de se}}
Laws against suicide (and attempted suicide) prevailed in English [[common law]] until 1961. English law perceived suicide as an immoral, criminal offence against God and also against the Crown.<ref>{{citation|title=Constitutional Aspects of Physician-Assisted Suicide After Lee v. Oregon|author=SM Canick|publisher=Am. JL & Med.|year=1997|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/amlmed23&section=9}}</ref> It first became illegal in the 13th century. Until 1822, in fact, the possessions of somebody who died by suicide could even be forfeited to the Crown.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holt |first=Gerry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-14374296 |title=BBC News - When suicide was illegal |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2011-08-03 |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>

Suicide ceased to be a criminal offence with the passing of the [[Suicide Act 1961]]; the same Act made it an offence to assist in a suicide. With respect to [[Civil law (common law)|civil law]] the simple act of suicide is lawful but the consequences of dying by suicide might turn an individual event into an unlawful act, as in the case of Reeves v Commissioners of Police of the Metropolis [2000] 1 AC 360,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk/pa/ld199899/ldjudgmt/jd990715/reeves01.htm |title=House of Lords - Commissioners of Police for the Metropolis v. Reeves (A.P.) (Joint Administratix of the Estate of Martin Lynch, Deceased) |publisher=Parliament.the-stationery-office.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> where a man in police custody hanged himself and was held equally liable with the police (a cell door defect enabled the hanging) for the loss suffered by his widow; the practical effect was to reduce the police damages liability by 50%. In 2009, the House of Lords ruled that the law concerning the treatment of people who accompanied those who died by assisted suicide was unclear, following [[Debbie Purdy]]'s case that this lack of clarity was a breach of her human rights. (In her case, as a sufferer from multiple sclerosis, she wanted to know whether her husband would be prosecuted for accompanying her abroad where she may eventually wish to die by assisted suicide, if her illness progressed.)

====Scotland====
Suicide directly involving only the deceased person is not by itself a criminal offence under Scots Law and has not been in recent history. However, attempting suicide might be a [[Breach of the peace]] if it is not done as a private act; this is routinely reported in the case of persons threatening suicide in areas frequented by the public. The Suicide Act 1961 applies only to England and Wales but under [[Scots Law]] a person who assists a suicide might be charged with murder, [[culpable homicide]], or no offence depending upon the facts of each case. Despite not being a criminal offence, consequential liability upon the person attempting suicide (or if successful, his/her estate) might arise under civil law where e.g. it parallels the civil liabilities recognised in the (English Law) Reeves case mentioned above.

===United States===
Historically, various states listed the act of suicide as a felony, but these policies were sparsely enforced. In the late 1960s, eighteen U.S. states had no laws against suicide.<ref>{{citation |volume=6 |publisher=Washburn L.J. |page=395 |date=1966–1967 |title=Medical-Legal Aspects of Suicide |author=Litman, Robert E. |url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/wasbur6&section=41}}</ref> By the late 1980s, thirty of the fifty states had no laws against suicide or suicide attempts but every state had laws declaring it to be a felony to aid, advise or encourage another person to die by suicide.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Approaches and commonalities of suicide |author=ES Shneidman |publisher=Suicide and its prevention |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=6d3777E9uAEC&oi=fnd&pg=PA14|page=24 |title=Suicide and Its Prevention: The Role of Attitude and Imitation|isbn=9789004086135}}</ref> By the early 1990s only two states still listed suicide as a crime, and these have since removed that classification.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} In some U.S. states, suicide is still considered an unwritten "[[common law crime]]," as stated in [[Blackstone's Commentaries]]. (So held the [[Virginia Supreme Court]] in 1992. ''Wackwitz v. Roy'', 418 S.E.2d 861 (Va. 1992)). As a common law crime, suicide can bar recovery for the late suicidal person's family in a lawsuit unless the suicidal person can be proven to have been "of unsound mind." That is, the suicide must be proven to have been an involuntary act of the victim in order for the family to be awarded monetary damages by the court. This can occur when the family of the deceased sues the caregiver (perhaps a jail or hospital) for negligence in failing to provide appropriate care.<ref>[http://www.jaapl.org/cgi/content/full/33/2/176 On Sound and Unsound Mind: The Role of Suicide in Tort and Insurance Litigation], ''Journal of the American Academy of Psychiatry and the Law'', 2005</ref>  Some American legal scholars look at the issue as one of personal liberty. According to [[Nadine Strossen]], former President of the [[ACLU]], "The idea of government making determinations about how you end your life, forcing you...could be considered [[cruel and unusual punishment]] in certain circumstances, and [[Justice Stevens]] in a very interesting opinion in a [[Right to Die|right-to-die]] [case] raised the analogy."<ref>[[n:ACLU President Strossen on religion, drugs, guns and impeaching George Bush#Gun rights|Interview with Nadine Strossen]], David Shankbone, ''[[Wikinews]]'', October 30, 2007.</ref>
Physician-assisted suicide is legal in some states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nightingalealliance.org/pdf/state_grid.pdf |title=Account Suspended |publisher=Nightingalealliance.org |date= |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref> For the terminally ill, it is legal in the state of [[Oregon]] under the [[Oregon Death with Dignity Act]]. In Washington state, it became legal in 2009, when a law modeled after the Oregon act, the [[Washington Death with Dignity Act]] was passed. A patient must be diagnosed as having less than six months to live, be of sound mind, make a request orally and in writing, have it approved by two different doctors, then wait 15&nbsp;days and make the request again. A doctor may prescribe a lethal dose of a medication but may not administer it.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/health/2009/03/05/washingtons-physician-assisted-suicide-law-takes-effect/tab/article/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Jacob | last=Goldstein | title=Washington's Physician-Assisted Suicide Law Takes Effect | date=March 5, 2009}}</ref>

In California, medical facilities are empowered or required to commit anyone whom they believe to be suicidal for evaluation and treatment.<ref>See [[Code 5150|California Welfare and Institutions Code section 5150]], for example.</ref>

In [[Maryland]], it is an open question as to whether suicide is illegal. In 2018, a Maryland man was convicted of [[attempted suicide]].<ref>http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-suicide-criminal-charge-20180222-story.html</ref><ref>http://www.myeasternshoremd.com/stardem/news/local_news/rare-attempted-suicide-charge-goes-through-caroline-court/article_3e8f7813-a2c6-555c-a8cd-7876e09013e3.html</ref><ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5441037/Mentally-ill-Maryland-man-convicted-attempted-suicide.html</ref><ref>http://www.stardem.com/opinion/columns/attempted-suicide-likely-not-a-crime/article_5cc4e7d0-ffbf-5cce-8eb4-bb7a503141ab.html</ref>

